function MSAModule() {
  const [infStage, setInfStage] = useState(0);
  return (
    <>
      <SH num="01" title="The Core Problem" sub="Why current LLMs can't achieve human-scale memory" />
      <Prose>Cognitive science estimates human lifelong memory at ~10⁹ bits ≈ <strong style={{color:"#00e5ff"}}>200-300M tokens</strong>. Current LLMs max out at ~1M. MSA bridges this 100-300× gap by making sparse attention the native memory mechanism.</Prose>
      <StatRow stats={[
        {value:"~300M",unit:" tok",label:"Human memory",color:"#4ade80"},
        {value:"~1M",unit:" tok",label:"Best LLM context",color:"#ff6b35"},
        {value:"100M",unit:" tok",label:"MSA achieves",color:"#00e5ff"},
      ]} />
      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.msa_table1} caption="Table 1 — Comparison of Long-Term Memory Methods. MSA uniquely achieves ALL desiderata: lifetime memory, high precision, O(L) complexity, no catastrophic forgetting, end-to-end trainable." figNum="TABLE 1" zoom />
      
      <DeepBlock title="▸ Three Memory Paradigms & Why They All Fall Short" color="#ff6b35">
        <Prose><strong style={{color:"#ff6b35"}}>Parameter-Based</strong> (LoRA, CPT, Titans): Strong integration but catastrophic forgetting, can't scale dynamically.</Prose>
        <Prose><strong style={{color:"#ffd93d"}}>External Storage</strong> (RAG, MemAgent): Scales to lifetime but retrieval is decoupled from model's latent space — optimization gap.</Prose>
        <Prose><strong style={{color:"#7ec8e3"}}>Latent State</strong> (DSA, RWKV, DeltaNet): Native representations but strict capacity-efficiency tradeoff. KV-based can't scale; linear attention forgets.</Prose>
        <Callout type="key">MSA breaks the tradeoff: latent state memory with sparse selection → O(L) complexity + high fidelity for what matters.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <SH num="02" title="Architecture: Sparse Attention" sub="Document-based retrieval replacing dense self-attention" />
      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.msa_fig2} caption="Figure 2 — MSA layer: doc processing with doc-wise RoPE → K,V,K^R projections → chunk-wise pooling → top-k selection → sparse attention with Global RoPE. L_aux supervises routing." figNum="FIG 2" zoom />
      
      <DeepBlock title="▸ Dual Projectors: Why two key spaces?" color="#00e5ff">
        <Formula eq={`K_i = H_i·W_K   V_i = H_i·W_V   (content)
K^R_i = H_i·W_KR               (routing)
Q^R_q = H_q·W_QR               (routing query)`} label="Eq 1 — Separate content & routing projections" />
        <Callout type="insight">Routing needs document-level relevance. Content needs token-level precision. Separate parameter spaces let each optimize for its objective via L_aux and L_LLM respectively.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Relevance Scoring → Top-k Selection" color="#ff6b35">
        <Formula eq={`S_ij = max_token( mean_head( cos(Q^R_t, K̄^R_ij) ) )
s_i = max_j S_ij   →   I = Top-k({s_i}, k=16)`} label="Eq 2 — Hierarchical scoring: mean heads, max tokens, max chunks" color="#ff6b35" />
        <Formula eq={`K_ctx = [{K̄_selected}; K_q]   V_ctx = [{V̄_selected}; V_q]
Output = Attention(Q_q, K_ctx, V_ctx)`} label="Eq 3-4 — Sparse context assembly" color="#4ade80" />
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Doc-wise RoPE: Train on 64K, Infer on 100M" color="#b388ff">
        <Prose>Each document gets independent position IDs starting from 0. Adding more documents doesn't change any document's encoding. Global RoPE for the query is offset by k, maintaining causal flow.</Prose>
        <Callout type="key">This is the extrapolation secret: per-document positions are bounded by document length G regardless of corpus size. Standard RoPE would assign positions up to 100M — far beyond training range.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Chunk Compression: 64× reduction" color="#b388ff">
        <Prose>All matrices segmented into P=64 token chunks, mean-pooled. 100M tokens uncompressed KV ≈ 10.8TB. After compression: ~169GB. Routing keys alone: ~56GB on GPU VRAM, content K̄,V̄ on CPU DRAM.</Prose>
      </DeepBlock>

      <SH num="03" title="Training Pipeline" sub="CPT warmup → main → two-stage SFT curriculum" />
      <DeepBlock title="▸ Two-Phase Loss Schedule" color="#ff6b35">
        <Formula eq={`Warmup: L = 0.1·L_LLM + L_aux    LR=1e-4
Main:   L = L_LLM + 0.1·L_aux    LR=6e-6`} label="Router-first, then generation-first" color="#ff6b35" />
        <Formula eq={"L_aux = -1/|P| Σ log[exp(s⁺/τ) / (exp(s⁺/τ) + Σexp(s⁻/τ))]"} label="Eq 5 — Supervised contrastive loss per MSA layer" color="#b388ff" />
        <Callout type="warning">Ablation: removing CPT causes -31.3% avg, -43.1% on HotpotQA. Routing errors compound in multi-hop chains.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <SH num="04" title="Three-Stage Inference" sub="Offline encoding → Online routing → Sparse generation" />
      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.msa_fig3} caption="Figure 3 — Three-stage inference with Memory Interleave: iterative routing for multi-hop reasoning." figNum="FIG 3" zoom />
      <DeepBlock title="▸ Stage Details & Complexity" color="#00e5ff">
        <Formula eq={`S1 (OFFLINE): O(LG) — encode corpus once
S2 (ONLINE):  O(ML/P) — route query vs cached K̄^R
S3 (ONLINE):  O(T·(M+kG/P)²) — generate (independent of L)`} label="Eq 6-7 — Linear overall complexity" />
        <Callout type="math">At 100M tokens: standard attention prefill ≈ O(10¹⁶) per query. MSA routing ≈ O(10⁸). Eight orders of magnitude difference.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Memory Interleave: Multi-hop Reasoning" color="#4ade80">
        <Prose>For "When was Erik Watts' father born?" — Round 1 finds Erik Watts doc → discovers father is Bill Watts → Round 2 retrieves Bill Watts doc → answer: May 5, 1939. Model adaptively decides docs per round.</Prose>
        <Callout type="key">Ablation: -19.2% on HotpotQA without interleave. Each hop is trained as a separate sample.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <SH num="05" title="Results" sub="QA benchmarks, NIAH, scalability" />
      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.msa_fig1} caption="Figure 1 — MSA maintains <9% degradation from 16K to 100M tokens. All other models collapse." figNum="FIG 1" zoom />
      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.msa_fig4} caption="Figure 4 — NIAH accuracy: MSA 95% at 1M tokens. Qwen3-4B backbone: 25%. Even 80B models: 81%." figNum="FIG 4" zoom />
      <StatRow stats={[
        {value:"3.760",unit:" avg",label:"QA (vs RAG 3.37)",color:"#00e5ff"},
        {value:"94.8",unit:"%",label:"NIAH @ 1M",color:"#4ade80"},
        {value:"<9",unit:"%",label:"Degradation 16K→100M",color:"#ffd93d"},
        {value:"4B",unit:"",label:"Beats 235B+SOTA RAG",color:"#ff6b35"},
      ]} />

      <SH num="06" title="Mental Models" sub="Intuitive framings" />
      {[
        {t:"🏛️ Library with Neural Catalog",a:"MSA = a catalog trained by reading every book. Asks which 16 books matter, reads compressed summaries. Unlike RAG's librarian who only reads titles.",tech:"Router Projectors trained E2E via L_aux. Compressed KV = 64× pooled chunks. Catalog (K̄^R) on GPU, books (K̄,V̄) on CPU.",c:"#00e5ff"},
        {t:"🏠 Independent Zip Codes (Doc-wise RoPE)",a:"Each city has its own numbering starting from 0. Adding cities doesn't shift existing addresses.",tech:"Per-doc positions bounded by G. Train on 64K, infer on 100M. Global RoPE only for query, offset by k.",c:"#b388ff"},
        {t:"🔍 Detective's Notebook (Memory Interleave)",a:"Interview witness A → learn name → find witness B → enough evidence → write report.",tech:"S2+S3 loop iteratively. Model decides docs per round. -19.2% on HotpotQA without it.",c:"#4ade80"},
      ].map((m,i) => (
        <div key={i} style={{background:"#0a1520",borderRadius:10,padding:20,marginBottom:12,border:`1px solid ${m.c}15`}}>
          <div style={{color:m.c,fontFamily:"var(--display)",fontSize:17,fontWeight:800,marginBottom:14}}>{m.t}</div>
          <div style={{padding:"12px 16px",background:`${m.c}06`,borderRadius:8,marginBottom:12,borderLeft:`3px solid ${m.c}50`}}>
            <div style={{color:"#c0d8e8",fontFamily:"var(--serif)",fontSize:13,lineHeight:1.7}}>{m.a}</div>
          </div>
          <div style={{padding:"12px 16px",background:"#060e18",borderRadius:8,borderLeft:"3px solid #00e5ff30"}}>
            <div style={{color:"#8ab4d0",fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:11,lineHeight:1.7}}>{m.tech}</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </>
  );
}

