// TURBOQUANT PAPER MODULE
// ════════════════════════════════════════
function TurboQuantModule() {
  const [algoTab, setAlgoTab] = useState(0);

  return (
    <>
      <SH num="01" title="The Core Problem" sub="Vector quantization: compressing high-dimensional vectors while preserving geometry" />
      <Prose>
        Vector quantization (VQ) traces back to <strong style={{color:"#f59e0b"}}>Shannon's source coding theory</strong> — the fundamental limit on how much you can compress data while bounding distortion. Modern AI needs VQ everywhere: KV cache compression in LLMs, model weight quantization, and nearest-neighbor search in vector databases. The core challenge: design a map Q: ℝᵈ → {0,1}ᴮ that compresses d-dimensional vectors to B bits while minimizing distortion in MSE and inner products.
      </Prose>

      <StatRow stats={[
        {value:"≈2.7×",unit:"",label:"Of info-theoretic bound",color:"#f59e0b"},
        {value:"3.5",unit:" bits",label:"Quality neutral KV cache",color:"#4ade80"},
        {value:"0",unit:" sec",label:"Indexing time (vs PQ)",color:"#00e5ff"},
        {value:"5×",unit:"+",label:"KV cache compression",color:"#b388ff"},
      ]} />

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Why This Problem Matters NOW" color="#f59e0b" defaultOpen>
        <Prose>Three critical applications drive urgency:</Prose>
        <div style={{display:"flex",flexDirection:"column",gap:8,margin:"10px 0"}}>
          {[
            {title:"KV Cache Compression",desc:"LLM context scales with sequence length × layers × heads. At 128K context, KV cache dominates memory. Must compress while preserving inner products (attention scores = q·kᵀ).",color:"#f59e0b"},
            {title:"Model Weight Quantization",desc:"Communication bottleneck between HBM↔SRAM on accelerators. Compress weights + activations → lower inference latency. Inner products between activations and weights are the core operation.",color:"#00e5ff"},
            {title:"Nearest Neighbor Search",desc:"Vector databases for RAG need fast inner product / cosine similarity. Product Quantization (PQ) compresses index but requires heavy k-means preprocessing. TurboQuant: zero indexing time.",color:"#4ade80"},
          ].map((a,i) => (
            <div key={i} style={{padding:14,background:"#060e18",borderRadius:8,borderLeft:`3px solid ${a.color}`}}>
              <div style={{color:a.color,fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:11,fontWeight:700,marginBottom:4}}>{a.title}</div>
              <div style={{color:"#8ab4d0",fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:11,lineHeight:1.6}}>{a.desc}</div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Formal Problem Definition" color="#b388ff">
        <Formula eq={`Q : ℝᵈ → {0,1}ᴮ      (quantization map, B = b·d bits)
Q⁻¹: {0,1}ᴮ → ℝᵈ    (dequantization / reconstruction)

bit-width b = average bits per coordinate`} label="Quantizer & Dequantizer" color="#b388ff" />
        <Formula eq={`(MSE)        D_mse := E[ ‖x - Q⁻¹(Q(x))‖² ]
(Inner-prod) D_prod := E[ |⟨y,x⟩ - ⟨y, Q⁻¹(Q(x))⟩|² ]
(Unbiased)   E[ ⟨y, Q⁻¹(Q(x))⟩ ] = ⟨y, x⟩`} label="Eq 1-2 — Distortion measures + unbiasedness requirement" color="#f59e0b" />
        <Callout type="key">Key constraint: worst-case vectors — no assumptions about data distribution. The quantizer Q(·) is randomized, expectations are over quantizer randomness. Unbiasedness is required for inner product estimation.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <SH num="02" title="The Core Insight: Random Rotation → Beta Distribution" sub="How randomization enables optimal scalar quantization" />

      <Prose>
        TurboQuant's brilliance is in its simplicity. The key mathematical insight: <strong style={{color:"#f59e0b"}}>multiply any unit vector by a random rotation matrix Π, and each coordinate of the result follows a known Beta distribution</strong>, regardless of the input. In high dimensions, coordinates become nearly independent. This means you can quantize each coordinate with an optimal scalar quantizer independently — and still achieve near-optimal vector quantization.
      </Prose>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Lemma 1: Coordinate Distribution on the Hypersphere" color="#f59e0b" defaultOpen>
        <Formula eq={`If x ∈ S^{d-1} is uniform on the unit sphere, then each coordinate:

x_j ~ f_X(x) = Γ(d/2) / (√π · Γ((d-1)/2)) · (1-x²)^{(d-3)/2}

As d→∞: f_X(·) → N(0, 1/d)  (Gaussian)`} label="Lemma 1 — Coordinate distribution of random point on hypersphere" />
        <Callout type="math">
          The proof is elegant: f_X(x) = ratio of (d-1)-sphere area at height x to d-sphere volume, scaled by Pythagorean factor. In high dims, concentration of measure + CLT → Gaussian. Crucially, distinct coordinates become <em>nearly independent</em> (not just uncorrelated — a deeper result from high-dimensional probability theory).
        </Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ From Beta Distribution to Optimal Scalar Quantizer" color="#00e5ff">
        <Prose>Now that we know the distribution, finding the optimal b-bit scalar quantizer reduces to a <strong style={{color:"#00e5ff"}}>1D continuous k-means problem</strong>:</Prose>
        <Formula eq={`C(f_X, b) := min_{-1≤c₁≤...≤c_{2^b}≤1}  Σᵢ ∫ |x - cᵢ|² · f_X(x) dx

Solved by Lloyd-Max algorithm → optimal Voronoi tessellation
Boundaries = midpoints between consecutive centroids`} label="Eq 4 — Optimal scalar quantization as 1D k-means" color="#00e5ff" />
        <Callout type="insight">
          For high-d (where f_X ≈ Gaussian): b=1 centroids are ±√(2/πd). b=2 centroids are {'{'}&plusmn;0.453/√d, &plusmn;1.51/√d{'}'}. These are precomputed once and stored — no per-data computation needed. This is what makes TurboQuant truly online / data-oblivious.
        </Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <SH num="03" title="Two Algorithms: MSE & Inner Product" sub="Why MSE-optimal quantizers are biased for inner products" />

      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.tq_fig1} caption="Figure 1 — Error distributions. TurboQuant_prod (top): centered at zero = unbiased across all bit-widths. TurboQuant_mse (bottom): shifted right = biased, especially at low bit-widths." figNum="FIG 1" zoom />

      <TabSwitcher tabs={[{label:"Algorithm 1: TurboQuant_mse",color:"#f59e0b"},{label:"Algorithm 2: TurboQuant_prod",color:"#00e5ff"}]} active={algoTab} onChange={setAlgoTab} />

      {algoTab === 0 ? (
        <div style={{padding:20,background:"#0a1520",borderRadius:10,border:"1px solid #f59e0b25"}}>
          <div style={{color:"#f59e0b",fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:13,fontWeight:700,marginBottom:14}}>TurboQuant_mse — Minimizing Mean Squared Error</div>
          <StepFlow color="#f59e0b" steps={[
            {title:"Random rotation",desc:"y ← Π·x where Π is a random rotation matrix (QR decomposition of random Gaussian matrix). Now each yⱼ ~ Beta distribution."},
            {title:"Scalar quantization",desc:"For each coordinate yⱼ, find nearest centroid: idxⱼ ← argmin_k |yⱼ - cₖ|. Centroids are precomputed from Lloyd-Max on the Beta distribution."},
            {title:"Store indices",desc:"Output: idx ∈ [2^b]^d — each coordinate encoded as a b-bit integer."},
            {title:"Dequantization",desc:"ỹⱼ ← c_{idxⱼ} for each coordinate. Then rotate back: x̃ ← Πᵀ·ỹ."},
          ]} />
          <Formula eq={`Theorem 1: D_mse ≤ (√3π/2) · 1/4^b  for any b ≥ 0

Precise values for small b:
b=1: 0.36   b=2: 0.117   b=3: 0.03   b=4: 0.009`} label="MSE distortion bound" color="#f59e0b" />
          <Callout type="math">
            Proof sketch: D_mse = d · C(f_X, b) because rotation preserves norms and all coordinates have identical Beta distribution. C(f_X, b) is bounded using Panter-Dite high-resolution formula for b&gt;4, or numerically solved for small b.
          </Callout>
        </div>
      ) : (
        <div style={{padding:20,background:"#0a1520",borderRadius:10,border:"1px solid #00e5ff25"}}>
          <div style={{color:"#00e5ff",fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:13,fontWeight:700,marginBottom:14}}>TurboQuant_prod — Unbiased Inner Product Estimation</div>
          <Callout type="warning">
            <strong>Critical insight:</strong> MSE-optimal quantizers are BIASED for inner products! At b=1, the bias is 2/π ≈ 0.64 — the estimator systematically underestimates inner products. A separate algorithm is needed.
          </Callout>
          <StepFlow color="#00e5ff" steps={[
            {title:"MSE quantize at b-1 bits",desc:"Apply TurboQuant_mse with bit-width (b-1) to get idx and reconstructed x̃_mse."},
            {title:"Compute residual",desc:"r ← x - x̃_mse. This residual has small L2 norm: E[‖r‖] = √C(f_X, b-1)."},
            {title:"QJL on residual",desc:"Apply Quantized Johnson-Lindenstrauss: qjl ← sign(S·r) where S is random Gaussian. This is a 1-bit quantization of the residual."},
            {title:"Store (idx, qjl, ‖r‖₂)",desc:"Total: (b-1)·d bits for MSE + d bits for QJL sign = b·d bits total."},
            {title:"Dequantization",desc:"x̃ = x̃_mse + √(π/2)/d · ‖r‖ · Sᵀ·qjl. The QJL term provides unbiased correction."},
          ]} />
          <Formula eq={`Theorem 2:
• Unbiased: E[⟨y, x̃⟩] = ⟨y, x⟩
• D_prod ≤ (√3π/2) · ‖y‖²/d · 1/4^b  for any b ≥ 0

b=1: 1.57/d   b=2: 0.56/d   b=3: 0.18/d   b=4: 0.047/d`} label="Inner product distortion bound" color="#00e5ff" />
          <Callout type="key">
            The two-stage trick: MSE quantizer minimizes ‖residual‖₂. Then QJL provides unbiased inner product estimation of the residual. Combined: unbiased overall with near-optimal distortion. The 1/d factor means distortion decreases with dimension — high-dimensional data is EASIER to quantize.
          </Callout>
        </div>
      )}

      <SH num="04" title="QJL: The 1-Bit Quantizer Foundation" sub="Quantized Johnson-Lindenstrauss transform — from the linked paper" />

      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.qjl_fig1} caption="QJL paper Figure 1 — Overview: key embedding k → JL transform S·k → sign quantization → 1-bit cache. Query q → JL transform S·q (unquantized). Inner product estimated asymmetrically." figNum="QJL FIG 1" zoom />

      <DeepBlock title="▸ QJL Definition & Unbiasedness Proof" color="#f59e0b" defaultOpen>
        <Formula eq={`QJL map:     Q_qjl(x) := sign(S·x)    where S ∈ ℝ^{d×d}, S_ij ~ N(0,1)

Dequantize:  Q⁻¹_qjl(z) := √(π/2)/d · Sᵀ·z

Estimator:   ProdQJL(q,k) = √(π/2)/m · ‖k‖₂ · ⟨Sq, sign(Sk)⟩`} label="Definition 1 (QJL) — 1-bit quantization via random projection + sign" color="#f59e0b" />
        <Prose>The proof of unbiasedness is elegant. Decompose q into its projection onto k and the orthogonal component q⊥ₖ:</Prose>
        <Formula eq={`E[ProdQJL(q,k)] = √(π/2) · [⟨q,k⟩/‖k‖ · E[|sᵀk|] + ‖k‖·E[sᵀq⊥·sign(sᵀk)]]

Second term = 0 (independence: q⊥ₖ ⊥ k → sᵀq⊥ and sign(sᵀk) independent)
First term: E[|sᵀk|] = ‖k‖·√(2/π) (half-normal moment)

→ E[ProdQJL] = √(π/2) · ⟨q,k⟩/‖k‖ · ‖k‖·√(2/π) = ⟨q,k⟩  ✓`} label="Lemma 3.2 proof — Unbiasedness via orthogonal decomposition" color="#b388ff" />
        <Callout type="insight">
          Critical subtlety: if you quantized BOTH q and k to sign bits, you'd get an estimator of the angle (à la SimHash/Charikar), not the inner product. The asymmetry — quantize k, leave q unquantized — is what gives unbiased inner product estimation. The √(π/2) scaling factor corrects for the sign quantization distortion.
        </Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Variance Bound & Attention Score Guarantee" color="#00e5ff">
        <Formula eq={`Lemma 4: Var[ProdQJL(q,k)] ≤ π/(2d) · ‖y‖²

Theorem 3.6 (from QJL paper):
If m ≥ 2r²ε⁻²log(n), then attention scores satisfy:
|Score_hat(i) - Score(i)| ≤ 3ε · Score(i)  for all i ∈ [n]`} label="Distortion bounds — relative error on attention scores" color="#00e5ff" />
        <Callout type="math">Key result: bits per token scales as O(log n) — logarithmic in sequence length, INDEPENDENT of embedding dimension. This means the compression ratio improves with higher-dimensional embeddings.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.qjl_fig2} caption="QJL paper Figure 2 — Outlier patterns in Llama-2 key cache. Early layers: no outliers. Deep layers: ~4 fixed channels have 5-8× larger magnitude. Solution: quantize outlier/inlier channels with separate QJL instances." figNum="QJL FIG 2" zoom />

      <SH num="05" title="Information-Theoretic Lower Bounds" sub="Proving TurboQuant is near-optimal via Shannon + Yao's minimax" />

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Shannon Lower Bound on Distortion Rate" color="#b388ff" defaultOpen>
        <Formula eq={`Shannon Lower Bound (Lemma 2):
D(p_X, B) ≥ d/(2πe) · 2^{(2/d)(h(x)-B)}

For uniform on sphere (Lemma 3):
D(B) ≥ 2^{-2B/d} = 1/4^b    (since B = b·d)`} label="Information-theoretic minimum distortion" color="#b388ff" />
        <Prose>The proof uses Stirling's approximation for the hypersphere area Aₐ and plugs into Shannon's lossy source coding theorem with backward Gaussian test channel.</Prose>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Theorem 3: The Full Lower Bound" color="#ff4444">
        <Formula eq={`Theorem 3: For ANY randomized quantizer Q with bit-width b,
there exist hard instances x, y ∈ S^{d-1} such that:

D_mse(Q) ≥ 1/4^b
D_prod(Q) ≥ ‖y‖²/d · 1/4^b`} label="Lower bounds via Yao's minimax principle" color="#ff4444" />
        <Callout type="math">
          Proof uses Yao's minimax: worst-case randomized algorithm = best deterministic algorithm on hardest distribution. The hardest distribution is uniform on the sphere. Then Shannon's lower bound applies. The inner product bound follows by pigeonhole: if MSE ≥ 1/4^b summed over d coordinates, at least one coordinate j has error ≥ 1/(d·4^b).
        </Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ The Gap: How Close is TurboQuant?" color="#4ade80">
        <Formula eq={`Upper bound (TurboQuant): D_mse ≤ (√3π/2) · 1/4^b ≈ 2.72 · 1/4^b
Lower bound (any algo):   D_mse ≥ 1/4^b

Gap = √3π/2 ≈ 2.72×  (constant, independent of b or d)

At b=1: gap is only ~1.45× (even tighter!)`} label="Optimality gap — within 2.7× of information-theoretic limit" color="#4ade80" />
        <PaperFigure src={FIGS.tq_fig3} caption="Figure 3 — Empirical validation: observed distortions closely match theoretical predictions. Both MSE and inner product error fall between upper and lower bounds." figNum="FIG 3" zoom />
      </DeepBlock>

      <SH num="06" title="Experimental Results" sub="KV cache, NIAH, LongBench, nearest neighbor search" />

      <PaperFigure src={FIGS.tq_fig4} caption="Figure 4 — Needle-in-a-Haystack: TurboQuant achieves 0.997 score = identical to full precision (0.997), even at 4× compression. SnapKV (0.858), PyramidKV (0.895), KIVI (0.981) all degrade." figNum="FIG 4" zoom />

      <DeepBlock title="▸ LongBench Results: Quality-Neutral at 3.5 bits" color="#f59e0b" defaultOpen>
        <div style={{overflowX:"auto"}}>
          <table style={{width:"100%",borderCollapse:"separate",borderSpacing:"0 4px",fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:10}}>
            <thead><tr>
              {["Method","Bits","SingleQA","MultiQA","Summ.","FewShot","Synth","Code","Avg"].map(h => (
                <th key={h} style={{padding:"8px 6px",textAlign:"left",color:"#5a7a9a",borderBottom:"1px solid #1a2a3a",fontSize:9}}>{h}</th>
              ))}
            </tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              {[
                {m:"Full Cache",b:"16",v:[45.29,45.16,26.55,68.38,59.54,46.28,50.06],h:false,c:"#5a7a9a"},
                {m:"KIVI",b:"3",v:[43.38,37.99,27.16,68.38,59.50,44.68,48.50],h:false,c:"#7a9ab0"},
                {m:"PolarQuant",b:"3.9",v:[45.18,44.48,26.23,68.25,60.07,45.24,49.78],h:false,c:"#7a9ab0"},
                {m:"TurboQuant",b:"2.5",v:[44.16,44.96,24.80,68.01,59.65,45.76,49.44],h:false,c:"#f59e0b"},
                {m:"TurboQuant",b:"3.5",v:[45.01,45.31,26.00,68.63,59.95,46.17,50.06],h:true,c:"#f59e0b"},
              ].map((r,i) => (
                <tr key={i} style={{background:r.h?"#f59e0b08":"transparent"}}>
                  <td style={{padding:"6px",color:r.c,fontWeight:r.h?700:400}}>{r.m}</td>
                  <td style={{padding:"6px",color:r.c}}>{r.b}</td>
                  {r.v.map((v,j) => <td key={j} style={{padding:"6px",color:j===6&&r.h?"#f59e0b":"#8ab4d0",fontWeight:j===6&&r.h?700:400}}>{v}</td>)}
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <Callout type="key">TurboQuant at 3.5 bits matches full precision (50.06 = 50.06) — absolute quality neutrality at 4.5× compression. Even at 2.5 bits (6.4× compression), only 1.2% degradation.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <DeepBlock title="▸ Nearest Neighbor Search: Zero Indexing Time" color="#00e5ff">
        <PaperFigure src={FIGS.tq_fig5} caption="Figure 5 — Recall@1@k across datasets. TurboQuant consistently outperforms Product Quantization (PQ) and RabitQ at both 2-bit and 4-bit." figNum="FIG 5" zoom />
        <div style={{overflowX:"auto",margin:"10px 0"}}>
          <table style={{width:"100%",borderCollapse:"separate",borderSpacing:"0 4px",fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:11}}>
            <thead><tr>
              {["Method","d=200","d=1536","d=3072"].map(h => (
                <th key={h} style={{padding:"8px 10px",textAlign:"left",color:"#5a7a9a",fontSize:10}}>{h}</th>
              ))}
            </tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td style={{color:"#7a9ab0",padding:"6px 10px"}}>Product Quantization</td><td style={{color:"#8ab4d0",padding:"6px 10px"}}>37.04s</td><td style={{color:"#8ab4d0",padding:"6px 10px"}}>239.75s</td><td style={{color:"#8ab4d0",padding:"6px 10px"}}>494.42s</td></tr>
              <tr><td style={{color:"#7a9ab0",padding:"6px 10px"}}>RabitQ</td><td style={{color:"#8ab4d0",padding:"6px 10px"}}>597.25s</td><td style={{color:"#8ab4d0",padding:"6px 10px"}}>2267.59s</td><td style={{color:"#8ab4d0",padding:"6px 10px"}}>3957.19s</td></tr>
              <tr style={{background:"#f59e0b08"}}><td style={{color:"#f59e0b",padding:"6px 10px",fontWeight:700}}>TurboQuant</td><td style={{color:"#f59e0b",padding:"6px 10px",fontWeight:700}}>0.0007s</td><td style={{color:"#f59e0b",padding:"6px 10px",fontWeight:700}}>0.0013s</td><td style={{color:"#f59e0b",padding:"6px 10px",fontWeight:700}}>0.0021s</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <Callout type="compare">TurboQuant indexing: 0.001 seconds. PQ: 240 seconds. RabitQ: 2268 seconds. That's 200,000× faster — effectively zero preprocessing. And TurboQuant achieves HIGHER recall.</Callout>
      </DeepBlock>

      <SH num="07" title="Mental Models" sub="Building intuition for the math" />
      {[
        {t:"🎲 The Rotation Trick",a:"Imagine you have a biased coin. You can't design an optimal betting strategy because you don't know the bias. But if you could magically transform any biased coin into a fair coin (known distribution), you could pre-compute the optimal strategy. Random rotation does this for vectors: transforms ANY worst-case vector into a random point on the sphere with known Beta-distributed coordinates.",tech:"Π·x for random rotation Π → uniform on S^{d-1} → each coordinate ~ Beta → precompute Lloyd-Max codebook once. Data-oblivious: the same codebook works for ALL inputs because the rotation erases input-specific structure.",c:"#f59e0b"},
        {t:"📐 The Residual Correction (Two-Stage)",a:"You take a photo (MSE quantization), but it's slightly off-color (biased). Instead of retaking the entire photo, you just note the color correction needed (residual) and encode that correction cheaply (QJL sign bits). The correction is tiny, so 1 bit suffices.",tech:"Stage 1: TurboQuant_mse at (b-1) bits → residual r = x - x̃ has small ‖r‖. Stage 2: QJL sign(S·r) at 1 bit → unbiased correction. Total: b bits. The variance of the correction is proportional to ‖r‖² which is already small from Stage 1.",c:"#00e5ff"},
        {t:"📏 Shannon's Speed Limit",a:"Shannon's source coding theorem is like the speed of light for compression: there's a fundamental limit on how well you can compress, no matter how clever your algorithm. TurboQuant drives at 2.7× the speed limit — remarkably close for such a simple algorithm.",tech:"Lower bound: D_mse ≥ 1/4^b (from Shannon + Yao's minimax). Upper bound: D_mse ≤ 2.72/4^b. The gap is a constant ≈2.7× independent of bit-width or dimension. At b=1, the gap shrinks to just 1.45×. This is achieved by a data-oblivious algorithm with zero preprocessing.",c:"#b388ff"},
        {t:"🏗️ Outlier Architecture",a:"In a building, most rooms are standard size, but a few are grand halls. You can't use the same furniture plan for both. Similarly, in LLM key embeddings, ~4 channels have 5-8× larger magnitudes in deeper layers. TurboQuant uses two separate quantizer instances: one tuned for normal channels, another with more bits for outliers.",tech:"Split channels into outlier (32) and non-outlier (96). For 2.5-bit target: outliers get 3 bits, non-outliers get 2 bits. Effective: (32×3 + 96×2)/128 = 2.5 bits. This is consistent with KIVI, KVQuant, and PolarQuant's outlier strategies.",c:"#4ade80"},
      ].map((m,i) => (
        <div key={i} style={{background:"#0a1520",borderRadius:10,padding:20,marginBottom:12,border:`1px solid ${m.c}15`}}>
          <div style={{color:m.c,fontFamily:"var(--display)",fontSize:17,fontWeight:800,marginBottom:14}}>{m.t}</div>
          <div style={{padding:"12px 16px",background:`${m.c}06`,borderRadius:8,marginBottom:12,borderLeft:`3px solid ${m.c}50`}}>
            <div style={{color:"#c0d8e8",fontFamily:"var(--serif)",fontSize:13,lineHeight:1.7}}>{m.a}</div>
          </div>
          <div style={{padding:"12px 16px",background:"#060e18",borderRadius:8,borderLeft:"3px solid #00e5ff30"}}>
            <div style={{color:"#8ab4d0",fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:11,lineHeight:1.7}}>{m.tech}</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}

      <SH num="08" title="Connection to QJL Paper" sub="The foundation TurboQuant builds on" />
      <Prose>
        TurboQuant's inner product algorithm directly composes with the <strong style={{color:"#f59e0b"}}>QJL (Quantized Johnson-Lindenstrauss) transform</strong> from the same research group. QJL is the 1-bit quantizer used on the residual in Stage 2. Key results from QJL:
      </Prose>
      <div style={{display:"grid",gridTemplateColumns:"1fr 1fr",gap:10,margin:"14px 0"}}>
        {[
          {title:"Zero Overhead",desc:"No quantization constants (zero points, scales) need to be stored per block. This saves 1-2 bits per number vs traditional methods.",color:"#f59e0b"},
          {title:"Unbiased Estimation",desc:"Asymmetric: quantize keys to 1 bit, leave queries unquantized. If both were quantized, you'd estimate angles (SimHash), not inner products.",color:"#00e5ff"},
          {title:"5× KV Compression",desc:"3 bits per FPN vs 16 bits baseline. No accuracy drop on LongBench QA tasks. Custom CUDA kernels for optimized computation.",color:"#4ade80"},
          {title:"Log(n) Bits/Token",desc:"Bits per key token scales logarithmically with sequence length n, independent of embedding dimension d. Compression improves with longer contexts.",color:"#b388ff"},
        ].map((c,i) => (
          <div key={i} style={{padding:14,background:"#060e18",borderRadius:8,borderTop:`3px solid ${c.color}`}}>
            <div style={{color:c.color,fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:10,fontWeight:700,marginBottom:6}}>{c.title}</div>
            <div style={{color:"#8ab4d0",fontFamily:"var(--mono)",fontSize:11,lineHeight:1.5}}>{c.desc}</div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </>
  );
}

// ════════════════════════════════════════
// PAPER LIBRARY
// ════════════════════════════════════════
function PaperLibrary({ onSelect }) {
  return (
    <div style={{ padding: "40px 24px", maxWidth: 900, margin: "0 auto" }}>
      <div style={{ marginBottom: 32 }}>
        <h1 style={{ margin: "0 0 6px", fontFamily: "var(--display)", fontSize: 32, fontWeight: 900, color: "#e0f0ff", letterSpacing: -1 }}>Paper Decoder</h1>
        <p style={{ margin: 0, fontFamily: "var(--serif)", fontSize: 15, color: "#5a7a9a" }}>Deep-dive deconstructions of frontier AI/ML research. Every formula explained. Every design choice justified.</p>
        <div style={{ marginTop: 8, fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 10, color: "#3a5a7a" }}>by Atikan (अति-कण) — Beyond the Particle</div>
      </div>
      <div style={{ display: "flex", flexDirection: "column", gap: 12 }}>
        {PAPERS.map((p) => (
          <div key={p.id} onClick={() => p.status === "ready" && onSelect(p.id)}
            style={{ padding: 24, background: "#0a1520", borderRadius: 12, border: `1px solid ${p.accent}20`,
              cursor: p.status === "ready" ? "pointer" : "default", opacity: p.status === "ready" ? 1 : 0.4, transition: "all 0.3s ease" }}>
            <div style={{ display: "flex", justifyContent: "space-between", alignItems: "flex-start" }}>
              <div style={{ flex: 1 }}>
                <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: 8, alignItems: "center", marginBottom: 8 }}>
                  {p.venue && <span style={{ padding: "3px 10px", borderRadius: 4, background: `${p.accent}12`, color: p.accent, fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 10, fontWeight: 700 }}>{p.venue}</span>}
                  {p.date && <span style={{ color: "#3a5a7a", fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 10 }}>{p.date}</span>}
                  {p.status === "upcoming" && <span style={{ padding: "3px 10px", borderRadius: 4, background: "#1a2a3a", color: "#3a5a7a", fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 10 }}>UPCOMING</span>}
                </div>
                <h2 style={{ margin: "0 0 4px", fontFamily: "var(--display)", fontSize: 20, fontWeight: 800, color: "#e0f0ff" }}>{p.title}</h2>
                <p style={{ margin: "0 0 10px", fontFamily: "var(--serif)", fontSize: 13, color: "#7a9ab0" }}>{p.subtitle}</p>
                {p.tags && <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: 5, flexWrap: "wrap" }}>
                  {p.tags.map(t => <span key={t} style={{ padding: "2px 8px", borderRadius: 4, background: "#0d1b2a", color: "#5a7a9a", fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 9, border: "1px solid #1a2a3a" }}>{t}</span>)}
                </div>}
              </div>
              {p.hero && <div style={{ textAlign: "right", marginLeft: 20, flexShrink: 0 }}>
                <div style={{ color: p.accent, fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 28, fontWeight: 900 }}>{p.hero.value}</div>
                <div style={{ color: p.accent, fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 10, opacity: 0.6 }}>{p.hero.unit}</div>
                <div style={{ color: "#3a5a7a", fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 9, marginTop: 2 }}>{p.hero.label}</div>
              </div>}
            </div>
            {p.status === "ready" && <div style={{ marginTop: 14, color: p.accent, fontFamily: "var(--mono)", fontSize: 11, opacity: 0.7 }}>→ Open deep-dive</div>}
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

